# Real-World Investigation

To apply everything I learned, I performed a complete Reverse Image Search investigation using the image below.
Instead of simply uploading the image and accepting the first result, I approached it as an OSINT investigation by asking several questions:

* Where was this image taken?
* What is the name of this location?
* Is the location still operational?
* What historical information is available?
* Can the location be verified using multiple sources?

Using Google Lens, Google Images, TinEye, and Yandex Images, I analyzed the image and compared the results from each platform.
After cross-verifying the findings, I successfully identified the location as Yongma Land (용마랜드), an abandoned amusement park located in Seoul, South Korea.
Further research revealed that Yongma Land was once a popular amusement park before closing due to declining visitor numbers.
Today, it is a well-known photography destination and has appeared in numerous Korean dramas,
movies, music videos, and travel blogs because of its nostalgic and abandoned atmosphere.
This investigation demonstrated how a single publicly available image can reveal valuable intelligence when analyzed systematically using multiple Reverse Image Search tools.


